ons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment has been made by NHS England of the specialist skills and knowledge required to commission dialysis.","false","Biography information for Yasmin Qureshi","Bolton South East","Yasmin Qureshi","215401"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157004","Department of Health","false","2014-11-25","<p>Information on the number and net ingredient cost of prescription items for paracetamol<sup>1</sup> dispensed in the community in England is in the table.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Prescription Items</p><p>(000s)</p></td><td><p>Net Ingredient Cost</p><p>(£000s)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>21,963.2</p></td><td><p>73,793.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>22,616.5</p></td><td><p>83,146.6</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><sup>1</sup>Excludes combination medicines. Includes multiple packs per item and a range of formulations, including those produced specific to patient needs</p><p> </p><p><em>Source:</em> Prescription Cost Analysis system provided by the NHS Business Services Authority</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","215407","2014-11-25T17:07:23.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157004/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157004/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157004/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-20","Paracetamol","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the cost to the public purse was of prescriptions issued for paracetamol in England in each of the last two years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Nick de Bois","Enfield North","Nick de Bois","215406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157005","Department of Health","false","2014-11-25","<p>Information on the number and net ingredient cost of prescription items for paracetamol<sup>1</sup> dispensed in the community in England is in the table.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Prescription Items</p><p>(000s)</p></td><td><p>Net Ingredient Cost</p><p>(£000s)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>21,963.2</p></td><td><p>73,793.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>22,616.5</p></td><td><p>83,146.6</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><sup>1</sup>Excludes combination medicines. Includes multiple packs per item and a range of formulations, including those produced specific to patient needs</p><p> </p><p><em>Source:</em> Prescription Cost Analysis system provided by the NHS Business Services Authority</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","215406","2014-11-25T17:07:23.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157005/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157005/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157005/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-20","Paracetamol","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many prescriptions have been issued for paracetamol in England in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Nick de Bois","Enfield North","Nick de Bois","215407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157006","Department of Health","false","2014-11-25","<p>The Government is determined to make sure children and young people get the mental health care they need, and are taking a number of steps to address this.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Children and Young People’s Mental Health and Wellbeing Taskforce was launched in August 2014 to look at how to improve children and young people’s access to mental health services which are more responsive to their needs. It will focus on innovative solutions to improve access to help and support across the sectors, including in schools, through voluntary organisations and online. The Taskforce will report next spring.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department has invested £7 million in new Children and Adolescent Mental Health Services specialised Tier 4 beds, £54 million into the Children and Young People’s Improving Access to Psychological Therapies programme and £3 million in MindEd, which provides clear guidance on children and young people's mental health, wellbeing and development to any adult working with children, young people and families. The Department is seeking to procure a new survey of child and adolescent mental health. We are also introducing a new waiting time standard to make sure young people with psychosis get prompt treatment.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Public Health England has recently published a framework that addresses the mental health of young people, commissioning the Institute of Health Equity to produce evidence based briefings on parenting programmes and publishing a briefing for head teachers which makes the link between education attainment and pupil health and wellbeing.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Public Health England will also be publishing a framework for local authorities to improve health and wellbeing outcomes for young people aged 10 – 24. In all these products, mental health and wellbeing are key features.</p><p> </p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb",,"2014-11-25T17:30:57.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157006/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157006/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157006/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-20","Mental Health Services: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to improve mental health services for young people.","false","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","215408"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157007","Cabinet Office","false","2014-11-25","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2014-11-25T13:50:02.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157007/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157007/answer","PQ 215436 ONS 417.pdf","PQ 215436 ONS 417.pdf","ONS Letter to Member - Lung Cancer Patients","ONS Letter to Member - Lung Cancer Patients","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157007/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-11-20","Lung Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what proportion of lung cancer patients survived for at least two years after diagnosis in each foundation trust area in each year since 2005.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","215436"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157008","Department of Health","false","2014-11-27","<p>The management of individual cases of <em>E.coli</em> bloodstream infections is the responsibility of local infection prevention and control specialists. However, the Department has asked its expert Advisory Committee on Antimicrobial Resistance and Healthcare Associated Infections to consider the options for reducing the number of <em>E.coli</em> infections, which are not always hospital acquired.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-11-27T17:18:51.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157008/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157008/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157008/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-20","E. Coli","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will issue guidance to hospitals so that a case of E.coli bacteria triggers the procedures that would be followed if a case of MRSA were discovered.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","215426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157009","Department of Health","false","2014-11-25","<p>Data on waiting times to see a general practitioner (GP) is not collected.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The 48 hour waiting time target was removed because it was too inflexible in meeting the needs of patients. The GP patient survey showed that the proportion of people who wanted to get an appointment within two days (and were able to) actually fell between 2008-09 and 2009-10 i.e. when the 48 hour target was in place.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-11-25T17:39:40.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157009/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157009/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157009/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-20","General Practitioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people in (a) each surgery in the North Derbyshire Clinical Commissioning Group area and (b) each Clinical Commissioning Group area in England were unable to get a GP appointment within 48 hours in each month since 2010.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","215434"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157010","Department of Health","false","2014-11-25","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-11-25T17:27:11.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157010/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157010/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157010/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-20","Lung Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of lung cancer patients in each foundation trust area received radiotherapy treatment in each year since 2005.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","215440"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157011","Home Office","false","2014-11-25","<p>No such estimate has been made. The police pension schemes are administered locally by police forces, so data on this specific issue is not held centrally.</p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-11-25T14:23:51.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157011/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157011/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157011/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-20","Police: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make an estimate of what it would have cost to have continued paying police widows' pensions to those widows or widowers who lost their serving husbands or wives between 1987 and 2006, before officers had the option to opt in to a scheme which permitted payments to continue to a surviving spouse on remarriage.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bingham","High Peak","Andrew Bingham","215397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157012","Home Office","false","2014-12-01","<p>On 17 November we expanded our Registered Traveller (RT) scheme: Australians and New Zealanders being two of only five nationalities who may join the scheme. The scheme gives regular travellers to the UK who meet the qualifying <br>criteria use of our ePassport gates or the EEA/RT lanes at Heathrow and Gatwick. We estimate that up to 75,000 Australians and 18,000 New Zealanders could now be eligible to join RT, expediting their clearance through the UK border. More details about RT can be found on <a href="https://www.gov.uk/registered-traveller" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/registered-traveller</a><br><br>There are a wide range of opportunities available to citizens of Australia and New Zealand to stay in the UK. We currently have no plans to change the Immigration Rules beyond these.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-12-01T12:43:54.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157012/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157012/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157012/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-20","Entry Clearances: Australasia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will amend visa regulations affecting citizens of Australia and New Zealand to allow them to stay in the UK.","false","Biography information for Bob Stewart","Beckenham","Bob Stewart","215446"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157013","Home Office","false","2014-11-27","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to PQ 214026 answered on the 20th November 2014.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-11-27T16:33:12.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157013/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157013/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157013/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-20","Home Office: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she plans to answer Question 214026, tabled by the hon. Member for Newport West on 10 November 2014.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","215443"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157014","Home Office","false","2014-11-25","<p>The final report of the Panel Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse will be shared with the Home Department before it is published. Decisions about how the Inquiry will interact with the Home Office on the final report will be taken when the Chairman is identified and is in place.</p><p />","Hornsey and Wood Green","Lynne Featherstone",,"2014-11-25T14:37:21.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157014/answer","Biography information for Baroness Featherstone","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157014/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157014/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-20","Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department expects to be shown successive versions of the final report and associated documents in the historic child abuse inquiry.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","215413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157015","Home Office","false","2014-11-25","<p>The number of Suspicious Activity Reports relating to the Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 submitted to the National Crime Agency, or its predecessor the Serious Organised Crime Agency, over the last five reporting years (October to September inclusive) is as follows:<br><br>2013-14 – 352,844<br>2012-13 – 315,671<br>2011-12 – 277,970<br>2010-11 – 246,939<br>2009-10 – 239,983</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-11-25T16:17:24.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157015/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157015/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157015/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-20","Proceeds of Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many Suspicious Activity Reports relating to the Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 have been submitted to the National Crime Agency in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","215386"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157016","Home Office","false","2014-12-15","<p>We have made no such estimate as the use of screening is conducted on an intelligence led basis as part of Border Force's multi-layered approach. <br><br>The screening of vehicles by Border Force is undertaken through a range of methods. These include Passive Millimetric Wave Imagers, carbon dioxide probes, body detection dogs and heart beat detectors. Border Force has investment in <br>detection technology over the last 18 months, includes a £2 million scanner upgrade, a further £400,000 committed to infra red camera technology, and a £1.3 million investment in specialist dog search teams, at the juxtaposed <br>controls.<br><br>The selection of vehicles for screening is made on an intelligence led basis. Border Force staff, their contractors and detection technology are deployed to meet the risk. <br><br>In 2013/14 Border Force and its contractors detected 18,000 clandestine attempts to enter the UK illegally at our juxtaposed controls. This represents an increase of over 60% from 2012/13. <br><br>The UK and French Governments have signed a joint declaration agreeing to work together to improve the quality of border controls. <br><br>Border Force deploys 7,500 specialist staff, five cutters at sea and spends £518 million a year protecting our borders.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-12-15T12:19:13.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157016/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157016/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157016/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157016/answer/previousversion/29846","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-20","Borders: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 19 November 2014 to Question 213850, what estimate she has made of the total number of vehicles entering the UK which were not subject to screening by either body scanning machines or dogs in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","215376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157017","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-11-25","<p>I answered a similar question on 20 November from the hon. Member for Wrexham and the position has not changed.</p><p> </p><p>Lady Justice Macur’s Review is entirely independent of Government and its timetable is a matter for her. She is on record as saying that her Review would be thorough and that she would not draw any conclusions until she had considered all the evidence. I am, however, confident that good progress has been made and the Review is nearing its completion. The Government looks forward to receiving Lady Justice Macur’s Report next year.</p>","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Simon Hughes",,"2014-11-25T12:59:49.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157017/answer","Biography information for Simon Hughes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157017/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157017/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-11-20","Child Abuse in North Wales Judicial Inquiry Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether he plans to publish the Macur Report before May 2015.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Mr Tom Watson","215377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157018","Home Office","false","2014-11-25","<p>The government condemns violence against women and girls in all its forms and is clear that political or cultural sensitivities must not get in the way of preventing, identifying and prosecuting practices like breast ironing.<br><br>There are currently no plans to commission a study to establish the prevalence of breast-ironing in the UK amongst the Western, Eastern and Central African disapora communities.<br><br>However, the government is working with local areas to support them to identify areas of need in their communities in order that they provide services to victims.<br><br>Where breast ironing is practised on girls it is child abuse and should be treated as such by all frontline professionals.<br><br>The clear legal frameworks that apply to child abuse apply to breast ironing.<br><br>As with any other form of child abuse, any cases should be referred to the police who will investigate and where appropriate work with the CPS to prosecute.<br><br>It is important that affected communities come together to speak out against such abhorrent practices and denounce them for the crimes they are.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hornsey and Wood Green","Lynne Featherstone",,"2014-11-25T14:39:03.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157018/answer","Biography information for Baroness Featherstone","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157018/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157018/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-20","Breast Ironing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will commission a study to establish the prevalence of breast-ironing in the UK amongst the Western, Eastern and Central African disapora communities.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","215393"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157019","Department for International Development","false","2014-11-25","<p>In June 2014 there were two members of staff with some responsibility for disability. In November 2014 there are now four staff working on disability and a Director appointed as Disability Champion.</p><p> </p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2014-11-25T17:28:19.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157019/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157019/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157019/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-11-20","Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many staff worked in her Department's central disability team in (a) June 2014 and (b) November 2014.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","215389"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157020","Department for International Development","false","2014-11-27","<p>Addressing violence against women and girls (VAWG) is a top priority for the UK Government and DFID. We have prioritised work to end VAWG and break the silence on all harmful traditional practices like breast ironing.</p><p> </p><p>Tackling the root causes and drivers of sexual and gender-based violence is essential to make progress on eliminating violence against women and girls. While we do not have programmes specifically addressing the harmful traditional practice of breast ironing, we are working to end all forms of violence against women and girls in whatever way it presents itself. Details of our VAWG programmes in 29 countries can be found on development tracker.</p><p> </p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2014-11-27T17:28:17.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157020/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157020/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157020/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-11-20","Africa: Breast Ironing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what her Department is doing to help end the practice of breast-ironing in Western, Eastern and Central African countries.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","215395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157021","Department for International Development","false","2014-11-25","<p>DFID has appointed a senior level managerial champion at Director level. Their role is to ensure that the disability framework is delivered throughout the department, demand accountability from teams and increase organisational ambition on disability.</p><p> </p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2014-11-25T17:27:43.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157021/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157021/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157021/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-11-20","Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether she has appointed a senior disability champion for her Department.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","215378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157022","Department for International Development","false","2014-11-27","<p>From 2012 to 2015, DFID is providing £196 million to Yemen to address urgent humanitarian needs; build communities’ resilience and deliver basic services; and support the political transition and economic reform to increase citizens’ confidence in government and lay the groundwork for longer-term stability and development. None of DFID’s funding is channelled directly through the Government of Yemen’s systems.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Since 2012, DFID has provided emergency and early recovery assistance to over 850,000 Yemenis; emergency food assistance to over 600,000; reached over 1 million through our nutrition programmes; and helped over 150,000 have better access to finance.</p><p> </p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2014-11-27T17:29:28.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157022/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157022/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157022/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-11-20","Yemen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what support her Department is providing to the government of Yemen.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","215422"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157023","Department for International Development","false","2014-11-27","<p>The UK is deeply concerned by recent events in Yemen. The political transition in Yemen must not be allowed to fail and we are supporting President Hadi, Prime Minister Bahah and all parties working constructively to implement the Peace and National Partnership Agreement, and Gulf Co-operation Council Initiative and Implementation Mechanism.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>DFID will continue to support the Government of Yemen’s political transition, including through a new constitution, referendum and elections, and their economic reform plans. We will also continue to meet urgent humanitarian needs, tackle malnutrition, deliver basic services and improve access to finance.</p><p><strong><br> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2014-11-27T17:30:00.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157023/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157023/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157023/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-11-20","Yemen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what plans she has to provide further support to the government of Yemen.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","215423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157024","Department for International Development","false","2014-11-26","<p>PPIAF does not finance the provision of infrastructure through either public or private schemes. Its role is to assist governments in developing countries to improve the enabling environment for the provision of basic infrastructure services by the private sector.</p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2014-11-26T16:27:47.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157024/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157024/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157024/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-11-20","Developing Countries: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what proportion of the Public Private Infrastructure Advisory Facility budget has been spent on (a) private and (b) public schemes for energy infrastructure in each of the last eight years.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","215460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157025","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-01-13","<p>HM Prison and Young Offender Institution Hindley’s role is to hold young adult men (aged between 18 and 21 years) and adult men (aged 21 and older). This ensures that the accommodation at Hindley is used in line with the National Offender Management Service’s Estate strategy, which is to provide the number and type of prison places required by the courts, configure the estate to give best effect to Ministry of Justice strategic policy priorities, support stakeholder objectives, and those of partner organisations and make the best use of taxpayers’ money.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-01-13T14:36:46.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157025/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157025/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157025/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-11-20","Hindley Young Offender Institution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what his policy is on the future of Hindley Young Offender's Institute.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","215510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157026","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-11-25","<p /> <p>Youth Offending Teams (YOTs) play a key part in the youth justice system and the Government recognises their valuable contribution to the recent successes of the system. We want to improve our understanding of how YOTs are operating and how they have evolved in light of the changing circumstances surrounding the delivery of local youth justice services. We are working closely with the Youth Justice Board to finalise the details of this stocktake, which will establish a clearer picture of how the YOT model is operating nationwide.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","215431 ; 215432 ; 215433","2014-11-25T17:33:34.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157026/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157026/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157026/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-11-20","Youth Offending Teams","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, by what date officials carrying out the youth offending team stock take, announced by the Minister for Prisons, Probation and Rehabilitation on 17 November 2014, are to report.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","215430"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157027","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-11-25","<p>Youth Offending Teams (YOTs) play a key part in the youth justice system and the Government recognises their valuable contribution to the recent successes of the system. We want to improve our understanding of how YOTs are operating and how they have evolved in light of the changing circumstances surrounding the delivery of local youth justice services. We are working closely with the Youth Justice Board to finalise the details of this stocktake, which will establish a clearer picture of how the YOT model is operating nationwide.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","215430 ; 215431 ; 215432","2014-11-25T17:33:34.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157027/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157027/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157027/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-11-20","Youth Offending Teams","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the job titles are of the officials from his Department who will be responsible for carrying out the fieldwork for the youth offending team stock take, announced by the Minister for Prisons, Probation and Rehabilitation on 17 November 2014.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","215433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157028","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-11-25","<p>Youth Offending Teams (YOTs) play a key part in the youth justice system and the Government recognises their valuable contribution to the recent successes of the system. We want to improve our understanding of how YOTs are operating and how they have evolved in light of the changing circumstances surrounding the delivery of local youth justice services. We are working closely with the Youth Justice Board to finalise the details of this stocktake, which will establish a clearer picture of how the YOT model is operating nationwide.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","215430 ; 215432 ; 215433","2014-11-25T17:33:34.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157028/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157028/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157028/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-11-20","Youth Offending Teams","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what data will be recorded in the youth offending team stock take, announced by the Minister for Prisons, Probation and Rehabilitation on 17 November 2014, aside from the data currently provided quarterly to the Youth Justice Board.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","215431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157029","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-11-25","<p>Youth Offending Teams (YOTs) play a key part in the youth justice system and the Government recognises their valuable contribution to the recent successes of the system. We want to improve our understanding of how YOTs are operating and how they have evolved in light of the changing circumstances surrounding the delivery of local youth justice services. We are working closely with the Youth Justice Board to finalise the details of this stocktake, which will establish a clearer picture of how the YOT model is operating nationwide.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","215430 ; 215431 ; 215433","2014-11-25T17:33:34.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157029/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157029/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157029/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-11-20","Youth Offending Teams","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what criteria will be used to decide which youth offending teams will be assessed as part of the youth offending team stock take, announced by the Minister for Prisons, Probation and Rehabilitation on 17 November 2014.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","215432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157030","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-11-27","<p /> <p>A new Governor was appointed shortly before the inspectorate visit as part of performance improvement measures and the Chief Inspector acknowledged the positive impact since his appointment. The Governor is now producing an action plan in response to the inspection. Remedial actions and timescales are being identified to improve all areas of identified weakness. Action plan progress will be monitored by NOMS internal audit mechanism and the prison rating system.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-11-27T17:28:19.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157030/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157030/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157030/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-11-20","Hewell Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the findings of the recent report by HM Inspectorate of Prisons on HMP Hewell.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","215380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157031","HM Treasury","false","2014-12-02","<p>The Government strongly supports the promotion of strengthened collective action and pari passu clauses in international sovereign bonds, and has called on the International Monetary Fund to take an active role in doing so. The Government hopes that the text in the G20 Communiqué will lend momentum to this process.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2014-12-02T16:25:07.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157031/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157031/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157031/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-20","Government Securities","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Annex to the communiqué published following the G20 Summit in Brisbane in November 2014, what steps the Government is taking to implement the call for the inclusion of strengthened collective action and pari passu clauses in international sovereign bonds and for their use to be actively promoted by the international community and private sector.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","215372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157032","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-26","<p>The Government believes that Low Emission Zones (LEZs) are one of a number of measures that can provide an opportunity to promote growth and reduce air pollution in urban areas. Defra provides guidance to local authorities on the design of LEZs such as which vehicles should be covered and what emissions standards they should meet. The Government believes that decisions on whether or not to introduce LEZs, and the vehicles they cover, should be a matter for local authorities.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Mayor of London is proposing to create an ultra low emission zone (ULEZ) where almost all the vehicles running during working hours are either zero or low emission. A public consultation on the ULEZ is taking place between 27 October 2014 and 9 January 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2014-11-26T16:12:27.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157032/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157032/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157032/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-20","Low Emission Zones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will take steps to bring scooters and motorcycles under present regulations on low emission zones.","false","Biography information for Robert Flello","Stoke-on-Trent South","Robert Flello","215439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157033","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-26","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>In July 2014, the Government’s support for shipowners and ports was successful in securing €29.5m of EU assistance under the TEN-T programme. All the projects received the full amount that they bid for. They are:</p><p>· €10m - Pilot project to deploy hybrid scrubber technology. (P&amp;O with ports of Dover / Calais / Hull / Rotterdam)</p><p>· €2.5m – Deployment of hybrid scrubbers. (DFDS with ports of Immingham / Gothenburg)</p><p>· €4.3m – Trial of Liquefied Natural Gas bunkering in Teesport. (Teesport and consortium)</p><p>· €12.7m – Retrofitting a ship with LNG engines and developing port infrastructure. (Portsmouth with Brittany Ferries, port of Caen and Zeebrugge).</p><p>Ultimately, operators will make commercial decisions. The Government is aware that there are ferry routes which industry considers are vulnerable, but this information is commercially sensitive. We are exploring with the European Commission whether a ferry route which is deemed to be vulnerable as a result of the new sulphur requirements could receive State Aid – and, if so, the parameters on which it could do so. Those discussions are ongoing.</p><p>I have had two exchanges of letters with Keith Brown MSP, Minister for Transport and Veterans, concerning the future of the Rosyth – Zeebrugge freight service and the options that were being considered. We both recognised that issues around State Aid would significantly restrict domestic support and I confirmed that we had written to the Commission about the provision of State Aid. I assured Mr Brown that the UK would continue to support applications for EU funding to assist eligible projects that helped mitigate the impact of the Directive.</p><p>The aim of providing assistance would be to help secure existing routes, which in turn, should help to secure employment. Any domestic funds that we provide to industry will need to provide value for money to the taxpayer and avoid distortions in a competitive market. However, there would be no direct link between these funds and the provision of employment and training for UK seafarers. This is already provided for separately, through the training requirements of the tonnage tax regime and through our Support for Maritime Training (SMarT) funding which we increased by 25% last year to £15m.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","215416 ; 215417 ; 215418 ; 215419 ; 215458","2014-11-26T09:39:12.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157033/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157033/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157033/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-20","Shipping: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 27 October 2014 to Question 211928, what discussions his Department has had with its Scottish counterpart on the Rosyth-Zeebrugge freight service operated by DFDS and that company’s announcement on the viability of that route following the introduction of the sulphur dioxide emission regulations.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","215415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157034","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-26","<p>It is Government policy that the provision of parking and other facilities for lorry drivers is a matter for the private sector and local authorities, who are best placed to judge local traffic conditions and needs. However, DfT Circular 02/2013, issued in September 2013, requires that all motorway and trunk road service areas and truck stops signed on or from the Strategic Road Network must offer free parking for two hours and free toilets with hand washing facilities to all motorists. Depending on the type of facility signed, some must offer shower and washing facilities to HGV drivers and hot food and drink to all motorists.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-11-26T16:10:17.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157034/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157034/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157034/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-20","Roads: Freight","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to improve daytime and overnight facilities for road freight drivers.","false","Biography information for Robert Flello","Stoke-on-Trent South","Robert Flello","215438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157035","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-27","<p>It is not possible to frame meaningful estimates of the regulatory impact of the proposed Regulation in these terms. In the short term, the main impact would be on administrative compliance costs of the ports within scope of the Regulation, rather than on trade volumes. However, the industry has expressed concern that the Regulation, were it to be implemented along the lines of the May 2013 Proposal, would be likely to have a serious adverse impact on port investors’ confidence, which ultimately could depress trade and employment in the sector.</p><p> </p><p>The Council General Approach text, which was agreed by Transport Council on 8 October, would result in a substantially lesser regulatory impact.</p><p> </p><p>The Commission published an Impact Assessment accompanying its Proposal in May 2013 [reference SWD (2013)181 final]. This postulated induced cost savings and increases in short-sea shipping and throughput at European ports which I regard as wholly unrealistic, especially in the UK context.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2014-11-27T10:49:23.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157035/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157035/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/157035/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-20","Ports: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment has been made of the potential effect on (a) employment, (b) maritime freight volumes and (c) passenger numbers at UK ports on the (i) North Sea, (ii) Channel and (iii) Irish Sea from the European Commission's Draft Regulation on market access to port services and the financial transparency of ports.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","215398"
